trans-unit.source: The simplified REST API sets for managing entities are as follows:
trans-unit.target: The simplified REST API sets for managing entities are as follows:

trans-unit.source: GET on any unoccupied naming node (for example, / or /test) is a discovery operation and returns an AtomPub feed listing children.
trans-unit.target: GET on any unoccupied naming node (for example, / or /test) is a discovery operation and returns an AtomPub feed listing children.

trans-unit.source: It will only return the “immediate node.”
trans-unit.target: It will only return the “immediate node.”

trans-unit.source: For example, if you have queues at A/B/C, and perform a GET on “/”, it returns “/A”.
trans-unit.target: For example, if you have queues at A/B/C, and perform a GET on “/”, it returns “/A”.

trans-unit.source: If you perform a GET on “/A”, it returns only “/A/B”, and so on.
trans-unit.target: If you perform a GET on “/A”, it returns only “/A/B”, and so on.

trans-unit.source: “GET” against any occupied node (for example, /test1/test2, /test1/example, or /test2) is a get operation and returns an <languageKeyword>AtomPub</languageKeyword> entry with the description.
trans-unit.target: “GET” against any occupied node (for example, /test1/test2, /test1/example, or /test2) is a get operation and returns an <languageKeyword>AtomPub</languageKeyword> entry with the description.

trans-unit.source: “PUT” against any unoccupied node is a create operation.
trans-unit.target: “PUT” against any unoccupied node is a create operation.

trans-unit.source: The request body is and <languageKeyword>AtomPub</languageKeyword> entry with the description.
trans-unit.target: The request body is and <languageKeyword>AtomPub</languageKeyword> entry with the description.

trans-unit.source: “DELETE” against any occupied node is a delete operation.
trans-unit.target: “DELETE” against any occupied node is a delete operation.

trans-unit.source: “DELETE” against any unoccupied node is ignored and returns success.
trans-unit.target: “DELETE” against any unoccupied node is ignored and returns success.
